{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20141210230617|637541286","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Rodney_Davis_(politician)","to":"Rodney Davis (politician)"}],"pages":{"35907710":{"pageid":35907710,"ns":0,"title":"Rodney Davis (politician)","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2014-12-30T19:36:43Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{Infobox politician \n| name=Rodney L. Davis\n|birth_name=Rodney Lee Davis\n| image name=Rodney Davis, Official Portrait, 113th Congress.jpg\n| imagesize=\n| state=[[Illinois]]\n| office = Member of the [[U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from Illinois's [[Illinois's 13th congressional district|13th]] district     \n| term_start = January 3, 2013\n| preceded = [[Tim Johnson (Illinois politician)|Tim Johnson]]\n| party=[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| birth_date={{birth date and age|1970|01|05}}\n| birth_place=[[Des Moines]], [[Iowa]]\n| death_date=\n| death_place=\n| spouse=Shannon Davis\n| children= \n| religion= [[Roman Catholic]] <ref>{{cite web|last=Rep. Rodney L. Davis|title=Roll Call|url=http://www.rollcall.com/members/46493.html}}</ref> \n| residence= [[Taylorville, Illinois]]\n| occupation= [[Politician]]\n| alma_mater= [[Millikin University]]\n| website= [http://rodneydavis.house.gov/ rodneydavis.house.gov]\n}}\n'''Rodney Lee Davis''' (born January 5, 1970)<ref name=smart>{{cite web|title=Rodney Davis' Biography|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/9622/rodney-davis#.Uye_KF5Ax4w|publisher=Project Vote Smart}}</ref>  is an [[United States|American]] member of Congress who has been the [[United States House of Representatives|United States Representative]] for [[Illinois's 13th congressional district]] since 2013. He is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]. Davis is running for re-election in 2014, having won the Republican nomination.<ref name=roll>{{cite news|last=Cahn|first=Emily|title=Ann Callis, Rodney Davis to Face Off in Targeted Illinois District|url=http://atr.rollcall.com/ann-callis-rodney-davis-illinois-primary/|accessdate=19 March 2014|newspaper=Roll Call|date=2014-03-18}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nDavis was born in [[Des Moines]] and is a lifelong resident of [[Taylorville, Illinois]] where he attended public school. Before attending college, he worked at a [[McDonald's]] that his parents operated.<ref>{{cite web|title=Illinois, 13th House District|url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/congress-legacy/illinois-13th-house-district-20121101|publisher=National Journal}}</ref>  He graduated with honors from [[Millikin University]] in 1992 with a degree in [[political science]].\n\n==Early political career==\nAfter graduating from college, Davis worked for then-Secretary of State [[George Ryan]].  In 1996, he lost a race for the state legislature.  In 1998, Davis managed the first re-election campaign for Illinois Congressman [[John Shimkus]].  Following the successful campaign, Davis accepted a position on Shimkus' congressional staff.  In 2000, Davis lost his second campaign, this time for mayor of his hometown, Taylorville. Davis served as Shimkus' Projects Director while simultaneously running for Congress.<ref name=\"pantagraph\">{{cite news|last=Petty|first=Allison|title=GOP picks Rodney Davis to face Gill|url=http://www.pantagraph.com/news/local/government-and-politics/elections/gop-picks-rodney-davis-to-face-gill/article_924e6638-a1dd-11e1-baa7-0019bb2963f4.html|newspaper=Bloomington Pantagraph|date=May 19, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==U.S House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n;2012\n{{Main|United States House of Representatives elections in Illinois, 2012#District 13}}\nOn May 19, 2012, the Republican County Chairmen for the 14 Illinois counties comprising the 13th district nominated Davis to replace Illinois Representative [[Tim Johnson (Illinois politician)|Tim Johnson]], who had announced in April that he would not seek re-election. In addition to Davis, other finalists for the nomination were Jerry Clarke, chief of staff to fellow U.S. Representative [[Randy Hultgren]] and Johnson's former chief of staff; [[Erika Harold]], a lawyer and winner of [[Miss America]] in 2003; and Kathy Wassink, a businesswoman.<ref name=\"pantagraph\"/> Davis was reportedly coaching his sons' little league baseball game when he was informed that he had been nominated.<ref name=\"stl\">{{cite news|title=GOP chooses Davis for US Rep. Tim Johnson's seat|url=http://www.pjstar.com/free/x639944668/GOP-chooses-Davis-for-U-S-Rep-Tim-Johnsons-seat|newspaper=Associated Press|date=May 19, 2012}}</ref>\n\nDavis narrowly defeated [[David M. Gill]] in the general election by a margin of 1,002 votes (0.3%).<ref>{{cite web|title=Ballots Cast|url=http://www.elections.il.gov/electioninformation/VoteTotalsList.aspx?ElectionType=GE&ElectionID=33&SearchType=OfficeSearch&OfficeID=6034&QueryType=Office&|publisher=Illinois State Board of Election}}</ref>\n\n;2014\n{{Main|United States House of Representatives elections in Illinois, 2014#District 13}}\nOn June 13, 2013, former Miss America [[Erika Harold]] announced she would run against Davis in the 2014 Republican primary.<ref>{{cite web|last=Last|first=Jonathan V.|title=Miss America vs. Mr. Incumbant|url=http://www.weeklystandard.com/articles/miss-america-vs-mr-incumbent_742472.html|publisher=The Weekly Standard}}</ref> The primary took place on March 18, 2014. The Republican field included Davis, Harold, and [[Michael Firsching]].{{citation needed|date=March 2014}} Davis won the primary. He will face Democrat [[Ann Callis]] in the general election on November 4, 2014.<ref name=roll/>\n\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title = [[Illinois's 13th congressional district]] Republican primary results, 2014<ref name=illprimary/>\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Rodney L. Davis\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = 27,816\n| percentage = 54.63\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Erika Harold\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = 20,951\n| percentage = 41.15\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Michael Firsching]]\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = 2,147\n| percentage = 4.22\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = 50,914\n| percentage = 100\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Agriculture|Committee on Agriculture]]'''\n**[[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on General Farm Commodities and Risk Management|Subcommittee on General Farm Commodities and Risk Management]]\n**[[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on Horticulture, Research, Biotechnology, and Foreign Agriculture|Subcommittee on Horticulture, Research, Biotechnology, and Foreign Agriculture]]\n**[[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Water Resources and Environment]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure|Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure]]'''\n**[[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Aviation|Subcommittee on Aviation]] (Vice Chair)\n**[[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Highways and Transit|Subcommittee on Highways and Transit]]\n\n===Legislation===\nDavis introduced the [[Hire More Heroes Act of 2013 (H.R. 3474; 113th Congress)|Hire More Heroes Act of 2013]] into the House on November 13, 2013. The bill would allow employers to exclude [[veterans]] receiving health insurance from the [[United States Department of Defense]] or the [[United States Department of Veterans' Affairs]] from their list of employees.<ref name=3474sum>{{cite web|title=H.R. 3474 - Summary|url=http://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/3474|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=10 March 2014}}</ref><ref name=HultgrenPR>{{cite web|last=Hultgren|first=Randy|title=Let's Give Jobs to Veterans: Hultgren Supports Hire More Heroes Act|url=http://oswego.patch.com/groups/rep-randy-hultgrens-blog/p/lets-give-jobs-to-veterans-hultgren-supports-hire-more-heroes-act|publisher=Osqego Patch|accessdate=11 March 2014|date=13 January 2014}}</ref> This would have the effect of keeping their list of employees shorter, allowing some small businesses to fall underneath the 50 full-time employees line that would [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act#Employer mandate and part-time working hours|require them to provide their employees with healthcare]] under the requirements of the [[Affordable Care Act]].<ref name=\"HultgrenPR\"/><ref name=PeteGOPeyes1>{{cite news|last=Kasperowicz|first=Pete|title=GOP eyes Dem help on ObamaCare|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/200316-gop-hoping-dems-help-expand-obamacare-exemptions|accessdate=11 March 2014|newspaper=The Hill|date=10 March 2014}}</ref> Davis said that the bill \"gives our small businesses another incentive to hire veterans, which helps to address the increasing number of unemployed veterans, while providing them with some relief from ObamaCare.\"<ref name=\"PeteGOPeyes1\"/>\n\n==Political positions==\nDavis voted for H.J.Res.59 - Continuing Appropriations Resolution, 2014, which resulted in the [[Government shutdown of 2013|Government Shutdown of 2013]]. After the vote, ''[[Politico]]'' reported that Davis also intended to vote for a bill that would end the shutdown, stressing that an agreement needed to be made and that \"Like most of those I represent, I remain opposed to Obamacare, but a government shutdown is absolutely unacceptable.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=FINAL VOTE RESULTS FOR ROLL CALL 504|url=http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2013/roll504.xml|accessdate=19 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-joint-resolution/59|accessdate=30 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|website=http://ballotpedia.org/Rodney_Davis_(Illinois)#Government_shutdown|accessdate=30 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=ISENSTADT|first1=ALEX|title=Vulnerable Republicans: End the shutdown|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2013/10/vulnerable-republicans-end-the-shutdown-97654.html|accessdate=31 October 2014|agency=Politico|date=10/113}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/bill/17368/46206/9622/rodney-davis-voted-yea-concurrence-vote-with-amendment-h-j-res-59-continuing-appropriations-resolution-2014#46206|website=Project Vote Smart|accessdate=31 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=How Rodney Davis voted on key votes|url=http://projects.washingtonpost.com/congress/members/D000619/key-votes/|accessdate=31 October 2014|agency=Washington Post}}</ref>\n\nDavis voted to repeal the [[Affordable Care Act]],<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.bnd.com/2013/12/03/2938971/how-will-health-care-law-affect.html | title = Health care glitches put twist on local congressional races | work = BND.com | author = Mike Fitzgerald | date = December 3, 2013}}</ref> and voted to re-authorize the [[Violence Against Women Act]].<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/political-fix/in-illinois-davis-preparing-for-marathon-race-for-congress/article_61beea42-f2af-55b8-978a-e118909dd607.html | title = In Illinois, Davis preparing for marathon race for Congress | work = St. Louis Post-Dispatch | author = Bill Lambrecht | date = May 20, 2013}}</ref>\n\nDavis considers himself pro-life, opposes public abortion funding, and is against religious institutions being required to offer health plans that include coverage for birth control.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/IL/Rodney_Davis_Abortion.htm |title=Rodney Davis on Abortion |publisher=Ontheissues.org |date= |accessdate=2014-08-12}}</ref>\n\nDavis supported the March 2013 budget that was proposed by [[Paul Ryan]].<ref>[http://rodneydavis.house.gov/issues/budget-and-debt ]{{dead link|date=August 2014}}</ref>\n\nDavis cosponsored the REINS Act (H.R. 367), a piece of legislation that would hold executive agencies responsible for costly regulations.{{citation needed|date=May 2014}}\n\nDavis is a proponent of building the [[Keystone XL Pipeline]] and increasing the production of coal and other natural resources.<ref>[http://rodneydavis.house.gov/issues/economy-and-jobs ]{{dead link|date=August 2014}}</ref>\n\nDavis supports the re-authorization of the Elementary and Secondary Education Act (ESEA) and [[No Child Left Behind]] (NCLB).<ref>[http://rodneydavis.house.gov/issues/education ]{{dead link|date=August 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nDavis married his high school sweetheart, Shannon, in 1995, and the couple currently lives in [[Taylorville, Illinois]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Electrodney.com|url=http://www.electrodney.com/index.php/about/}}</ref>  They have three children.<ref name=\"pantagraph\"/>  Davis also holds various positions throughout his community. Davis serves on the Board of Education for St. Mary's Church, where he also serves as Athletic Director.<ref>{{cite web|title=St. Mary School|url=http://www.st-maryschool.com/boe.html|publisher=St. Mary's Church}}</ref> He coaches Taylorville Junior Football, is a member of the Taylorville Optimist Club, and serves on the Board of Directors for the Christian County Senior Center.<ref name=smart/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://rodneydavis.house.gov/ Congressman Rodney Davis] official U.S. House website\n*[http://www.electrodney.com Rodney Davis for Congress] \n*{{DMOZ|Regional/North_America/United_States/Illinois/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Rodney_Davis_%5BR-13%5D|Rodney Davis}}\n*{{CongLinks | congbio = D000619 | ballot = Rodney_Davis_(Illinois) | nndb = | votesmart = 9622 | govtrack = 412536 | opencong = 412536 | rollcall = 46493 | politifact = | ontheissues = IL/Rodney_Davis.htm | fec = H2IL13120 | opensecrets = N00034784 | assets = | legistorm = | followthemoney = 46856 | c-span = rodneydavis02 | rose = | imdb = | bloomberg = | nyt =  | wsj = | washpo = 96fa7cca-4bbb-11e2-8758-b64a2997a921 }}\n* {{ballotpedia|Rodney_Davis_Illinois}}\n* {{cite web|title=United States House of Representatives elections in Illinois, 2014|url=http://ballotpedia.org/United_States_House_of_Representatives_elections_in_Illinois,_2014|publisher=Ballotpedia}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{USRepSuccessionBox\n| state = Illinois\n| district = 13\n| before = [[Tim Johnson (Illinois politician)|Tim Johnson]]\n| years = 2013-Present\n| after = Incumbent}}\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Steve Daines]]<br><small>R-[[Montana]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=''[[List of current members of the United States House of Representatives by seniority|United States Representatives by seniority]]''|years=373rd}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[John Delaney (Maryland politician)|John Delaney]]<br><small>D-[[Maryland]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{IL-FedRep}}\n\n{{Persondata\n| NAME              = Davis, Rodney L.\n| ALTERNATIVE NAMES = \n| SHORT DESCRIPTION = Illinois politician\n| DATE OF BIRTH     = January 5, 1970\n| PLACE OF BIRTH    = Des Moines, Iowa\n| DATE OF DEATH     = \n| PLACE OF DEATH    = \n}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davis, Rodney L.}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Illinois Republicans]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Illinois]]\n[[Category:United States congressional aides]]\n[[Category:Millikin University alumni]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Des Moines, Iowa]]\n[[Category:People from Christian County, Illinois]]\n[[Cate